  p February 2017 Rev. Chris Lee started trying to grow his!{' '}
    a(href="https://www.instagram.com/p/B5cmnDuA5G9/" target="_blank") Instagram account
    |. He posted mostly pictures of himself, his family, and the church, and for two and a half years his account grew steadily.
  p July 2019 things changed. Chris started uploading!{' '}
    a(href="https://www.instagram.com/p/BzsoGX7gHe3/" target="_blank") “60 second sermons”
    |. The next five months saw him go from averaging!{' '}
    span.bold 1,000
    |!{' '}new followers each month to!{' '}
    span.bold 10,000
    |.
  img(src="https://harrydry.s3.amazonaws.com/gdmarketing/revchris1.png" alt="Rev Chris 60s sermon Instagram Growth").img__95
  p Here's a little compilation of Chris in action:
  video(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/revchris.mp4" class="img__55" playsinline="playsinline" preload="auto" controls="controls")
  //- p Why does it work?
  //- p The format is wonderfully simple. It's a little masterclass in some social media fundementals:
  p The format is wonderfully simple. It's also a great reminder of some social media fundementals:
  h2.under 1) Give people a reason to follow you
  //- p The first question to answer before posting on social media is, “Why should someone follow us?”
  p Chris’s “60 second sermons” give his account a clear!{' '}
    span.bold purpose
    | .
  p You can’t tell your friend, “You should follow this Priest”. But you can say, “You should follow this Priest... He posts these 60 second sermons”.
  h2.under 2) Your content should match the platform
  p Instagram is a light medium. Chris packages his content to reflect that.
  p He doesn’t preach from the pulpit. His “sermons” aren’t polished. He walks down the street holding an iPhone. And that's what people like to consume on Instagram.
  h2.under 3) Don't ask for anything in return
  p Chris records his sermons, uploads them for free, and never asks for anything in return. First his Instagram grew, and more recently!{' '}
    | his own congregation has grown as well.
